  "game_explanation": "This game has a strong hidden-value asymmetry that should shape bargaining. Buffalo values BLUE highly ($0.70) and RED very little ($0.10), so buffalo most wants to turn RED into BLUE or, secondarily, into GREEN. Bear values BLUE most ($1.00) and also values RED fairly well ($0.60), so bear is reluctant to give up BLUE and is happiest acquiring RED cheaply, especially by paying GREEN. Goose values GREEN at $0.50 but both RED and BLUE at only $0.10, so goose is the natural seller of GREEN if compensated with enough low-value chips, but goose has little reason to part with GREEN for a single cheap chip. Because acceptance is based on each responder's private surplus calculator, accepted trades should generally create nonnegative private gains for both sides. The largest bilateral gains are likely when bear buys RED with GREEN, because RED is much more valuable to bear than to buffalo or goose. Buffalo may try ambitious offers early, perhaps asking for GREEN or BLUE in exchange for RED, but such offers risk rejection if too one-sided. Goose, seeing only own payoffs, is likely to accept trades that convert low-value RED or BLUE into GREEN and to reject trades that surrender GREEN for too little. Uncertainty remains because proposers do not know others' exact values, and if both non-senders see a positive payoff they may both accept, creating random matching. Still, the most likely path is repeated pressure toward RED-for-GREEN trades with bear as the main demander of RED, limited BLUE trading because both buffalo and especially bear value BLUE too much to sell cheaply.",
