  "game_explanation": "This game is likely dominated by bilateral gains from trading RED away from dog-blue-6080 and toward the other two players only if the price is low enough, plus potential gains from moving BLUE toward butterfly-blue-3807. The strongest private-value asymmetry is that dog values RED at $1.00 while ram values it at only $0.40 and butterfly at $0.60, so dog is very unlikely to sell RED cheaply. Butterfly values BLUE highly at $0.90 while dog values BLUE at $0.20 and ram at $0.10, so butterfly has strong incentives to acquire BLUE, and dog in particular can profitably part with BLUE. GREEN is common at $0.50 for everyone, so it naturally serves as a medium of exchange because its value is common knowledge to each player about themselves but not known to others in play. Since each responder sees their own exact surplus from a posted trade, individually loss-making offers should usually be declined. Because multiple acceptances are randomly assigned, proposers also have some incentive to post offers that are acceptable to either counterpart, though private-value uncertainty makes this hard. The most likely efficient pattern is that dog trades away BLUE for GREEN or possibly for RED only at a favorable rate, butterfly aggressively seeks BLUE by paying GREEN or some RED, and ram, who values BLUE least and RED below GREEN, is most willing to surrender BLUE or RED in exchange for GREEN. With only three rounds and no direct knowledge of others' values, proposals are likely to be simple, exploratory, and often framed around GREEN-for-BLUE trades. A plausible full path is that dog successfully sells BLUE for GREEN to butterfly, butterfly then acquires more BLUE from ram using GREEN, and ram later tries modest GREEN-seeking trades using low-valued BLUE. As holdings evolve, butterfly's willingness to keep buying BLUE remains strong, while dog becomes less able to sell BLUE after early successful trades.",
